sp.p:
My lord, I over-rode him on the way;


And he is furnish'd with no certainties


More than he haply may retail from me.

I ran from Shrewsbury, my noble lord;


Where hateful death put on his ugliest mask


To fright our party.

The question then, Lord Hastings, standeth thus;


Whether our present five and twenty thousand


May hold up head without Northumberland?

I must wait upon my lord
here;
I thank you, good Sir John.

A better than thou: I am a gentleman;
thou art
a drawer.

A peace is of the nature of a conquest;


For then both parties nobly are subdued,


And neither party loser.

I am a knight, sir;
and my name is
Colevile of the dale.

Let there be no noise made, my gentle friends;


Unless some dull and favorable hand


Will whisper music to my weary spirit.

Not so much noise, my lords:
sweet prince, speak low;
The king your father is disposed to sleep.

O, good my lord, you have lost a friend indeed;


And I dare swear you borrow not that face


Of seeming sorrow, it is sure your own.

Well, you must now speak Sir John
Falstaff fair;


Which swims against your stream of quality.

This Davy serves you for good uses;
he is your
serving-man and your husband.

Come, you rogue, come;
bring me to
a justice.

Come, you thin thing;
come, you
rascal.
